SIMPLE: mister
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mister
<hw>Mis"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Master</er>,
and cf. <er>Mistress</er>.]</ety> <def>A title of courtesy prefixed to
the name of a man or youth. It is usually written in the abbreviated
form <abbr>Mr.</abbr></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To call your name, inquire your where,⟦br⟧
Or what you think of <qex>Mister</qex> Some-one's book,⟦br⟧
Or <qex>Mister</qex> Other's marriage or decease.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mister
<hw>Mis"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To address or mention by the
title Mr.; <as>as, he <ex>mistered</ex> me in a formal way</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mister
<hw>Mis"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mistier</ets> trade,
office, ministry, need, F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧tier</ets> trade, fr. L.
<ets>ministerium</ets> service, office, ministry. See <er>Ministry</er>,
<er>Mystery</er> trade.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>mester</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trade, art, or
occupation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In youth he learned had a good <qex>mester</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manner; kind; sort.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But telleth me what <qex>mester</qex> men ye be.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Need; necessity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Rom. of R.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mister
<hw>Mis"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be needful or of use.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for my name, it <qex>mistereth</qex> not to tell.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misterm</ent>⟦br⟧
